<TEXT>
a government report today said a failure of 
police control led to the deaths of 95 people who were crushed in 
a surging crowd at a soccer match and it recommended new safety 
measures for all stadiums 
the 71page report said authorities at hillsborough stadium in 
sheffield did not recognize how big their job would be or know how 
to cope when problems developed in the opening minutes of an april 
15 football association cup semifinal 
after the reports release sheffields top police officer 
south yorkshire chief constable peter wright submitted his 
resignation and david duckenfield who was in charge of police at 
hillsborough was suspended pending further review 
wright said he accepted full responsibility for police 
action which had unraveled like a handknitted rug with 
terrible consequences to the families who lost loved ones 
the report said drinking by an unruly minority of fans and 
confused and inadequate signs and tickets issued by the clubs 
aggravated the problem 
but it primarily blamed senior police officials 
neither their handling of problems on the day nor their 
account of it in evidence showed the qualities of leadership 
expected of their rank it said the main reason for the 
disaster was the failure of police control 
the crush occurred when fans in a standingroom section near the 
field were crushed against a steel fence by hundreds of people who 
surged into the stadium behind them 
the report recommended a 15 percent reduction in standingroom 
sections at british soccer stadiums and better safety procedures 
near the steel fences designed to keep rowdy fans off the field 
the report was sent for review to the home office where 
secretary douglas hurd said officials had failed to learn from past 
problems including the heysel riots in brussels and the bradford 
city fire that killed more than 50 people in britain 
the tragedy would not have occurred if lessons learned in the 
past had been properly applied hurd said 
rogan taylor president of the football supporters association 
said he was pleased with the report but that it did not eliminate 
the possibility of future stadium tragedies 
when 50000 people gather together theres a risk of 
something like this happening he said i think his report is 
trying to reduce that risk 
a lack of advance work and inadequate communication led to a 
buildup of fans outside the leppings lane entrance to the stadium 
where liverpool was playing nottingham forest the report said 
once police ordered a large gate be opened to let fans in just 
before kickoff there was inadequate effort to direct them away 
from an already packed standingroom section 
a surge of hundreds of liverpool fans into the area known as 
pen 3 pushed those already there forward crushing victims against 
metal fences or concrete floors and walls it said 
failure to cut off access to the central pens was the main 
cause of the tragedy justice peter taylor who headed the inquiry 
said in the report 
they were already overfull because no safe maximum capacities 
had been laid down when the influx entered pen 3 the layout of 
the barriers afforded less protection than it should and a barrier 
collapsed again the lack of vigilant monitoring caused a sluggish 
reaction 
the club and police should have realized that the turnstile 
area could not easily cope with the large numbers demanded of it 
unless they fans arrived steadily over a lengthy period 
officials said the reports recommendations should be 
implemented to insure safety during the new english soccer season 
starting aug 19 
