about 1000 chinese swamped government 
offices for a third day in a row friday apparently prompted by 
rumors it was easy to gain asylum in belgium officials said 
we dont know who started the rumors but there is not a grain 
of truth to it said justice ministry spokesman jeanfrancois 
raskin 
almost all of the chinese have been coming from the netherlands 
he said others have driven in from france and west germany most 
work illegally in restaurants or the garment industry in those 
countries and have no official documents he said 
since wednesday they have lined the street leading to the main 
refugee center in brussels they have not been deterred by official 
leaflets explaining the difficulties of gaining refugee status 
raskin said all requests that have been investigated during the 
recent surge have been turned down instead the applicants have 
received orders to leave belgium police have increased controls 
along the border he said 
newspapers reported the confusion may have arisen after the 
justice ministry said that following the crackdown on the 
prodemocracy movement in beijing chinese already living in 
belgium could ask for an extension of their residency permits 
belgium approved legislation last year to limit foreign 
refugees arguing it wanted to stop those people who falsely claim 
to be political refugees but only come to belgium to find work 
