a senior romanian diplomat charged with 
passing secrets to a foreign power has gone on trial in 
bucharest and faces the death penalty if convicted an emigre 
source said friday 
the trial for mircea raceanu is taking place behind closed 
doors said the source a spokesman for the parisbased romanian 
league of human rights 
raceanu served for several years in the romanian embassy in 
washington in the 1970s 
the trial was not reported by romanias statecontrolled media 
and a league spokesman told the associated press in vienna it was 
not known when it would end 
a brief announcement from the general prosecutors office 
carried by romanian dailies in march said state security bodies had 
uncovered a grave action of betrayal of the interests of the 
romanian people and state by raceanu 
raceanu last held the post of deputy head of the foreign 
ministrys us desk in bucharest he was said by emigre sources to 
have been detained jan 31 as he went with his wife to the us 
ambassadors residence to see a movie 
being caught in the act and following the investigations it 
has been found that since 1974 when mircea raceanu was recruited 
by a foreign spying service and became its agent he has been 
engaged in steady treasonable action the official agerpres news 
agency said last spring quoting the general prosecutors statement 
it said he managed to supply unspecified secret data and 
intelligence to the unidentified power for which he allegedly 
worked 
the maximum penalty for treason is death if the alleged 
espionage is deemed to have caused grave damage to state security 
the next most severe penalty is 20 years in jail 
the prominent media attention given to the arrest indicated 
authorities wanted to make an example of him following signs of 
domestic resistance to the tough policies of president nicolae 
ceausescu 
