<TEXT>
the house today passed a 2865 billion 
defense spending bill and lawmakers struggled to find final 
agreement on a savings and loan bailout as congress rushed toward 
its summer recess 
the military bill which was approved on a vote of 312105 
eliminates funds for president bushs proposed advanced tactical 
fighter and advanced cruise missile but restores money for the 
f14d jet that he wants to kill 
it also slashes nearly 2 billion for star wars from the 
presidents request strictly limits the b2 stealth bomber program 
and makes drastic cuts in the mx and midgetman nuclear missiles 
the white house budget office said before the vote that bushs 
senior advisers would recommend he veto the measure because it 
would severely compromise the administrations objective of 
providing adequate defense capabilities within constrained 
resources 
meanwhile house speaker thomas s foley urged his democratic 
colleagues to support a compromise 159 billion savings and loan 
bailout plan saying congress cannot start its summer recess 
without acting to stem continuing losses in the industry to 
delay it or defeat it that will cost money he said 
bush added his endorsement of the compromise plan in a letter to 
congressional leaders that said this legislation has been 
developed in a bipartisan process it is badly needed and must be 
enacted without further delay i ask that the house and senate 
approve this legislation today 
foley told reporters that many in his party have misgivings 
about the latest deal negotiated to salvage a rescue plan that has 
gone through a host of changes in recent weeks 
i think this bill needs to be passed he said although the 
washington democrat said his party had been reluctant to agree to 
any plan that would put bailout spending off the federal budget 
as the latest compromise proposes 
this is a compromise that we didnt prefer to make he said 
but he said that because bush has been adamant about taking it 
off budget we had to deal with that 
the senate today also passed on a 990 vote legislation to 
boost financial liability for oil spills create a nationwide 
system to clean them up and establish a 1 billion trust fund to 
help compensate for damages the bill was prompted by the accident 
involving the tanker exxon valdez this year 
and the house approved a compromise proposal to provide 895 
million to farmers suffering crop losses this year from drought and 
other weatherrelated damage the measure was passed on unanimous 
consent without a recorded vote and sent back to the senate 
