the senate voted friday night to temporarily 
extend the governments debt limit by 70 billion to 287 
trillion granting it authority to borrow enough money to function 
through the next three months 
on a voice vote the senate gave final approval to the extension 
and sent it to president bush for his signature 
had the lawmakers not approved the measure before leaving for 
their fourweek summer recess the government would have run out of 
money during their vacation and toppled into an unprecedented 
default 
the bill which the house had approved on tuesday provides 
enough borrowing authority to see the government through oct 31 
on nov 1 the temporary authority would lapse and the legal limit 
on the federal debt will lapse back to its current ceiling of 28 
trillion 
by that time lawmakers hope to complete a longrange permanent 
debt limit extension to more than 31 trillion enough borrowing 
for about a year 
many legislators hope the longterm extension will contain the 
elements of a budget deal between congress and the bush 
administration for fiscal 1991 which begins oct 1 1990 
legislative leaders spent much of the last several weeks trying 
to dissuade lawmakers from offering amendments to the debt limit 
measure the extension considered mustpass legislation is a 
favorite target for members of congress with bills that are too 
controversial to pass if standing alone 
the government needs legal authority to borrow money because it 
runs a deficit every year a shortfall that has hovered at around 
150 billion annually for the last three years it gets the rest of 
the money it needs each year by borrowing it 
when the reagan administration took office in 1981 the national 
debt was just above 900 billion 
