<TEXT>
the bush administration and congressional 
negotiators reached agreement thursday night on financing a 
sweeping 159 billion bailout of the savings and loan industry 
after senate republicans torpedoed a democratic plan 
the compromise was reached after a series of fastpaced 
developments in which president bush threatened to veto the bill 
the democraticcontrolled house ignored him in on a 221199 vote in 
favor of it and senate democrats fell six votes short of mustering 
the 60 needed to complete action 
that automatically tossed the bill back into a housesenate 
conference committee which locked up the deal after 11 pm 
approval is expected by the full senate and then the house on 
friday the last day before the august colngressional vacation 
treasury secretary nicholas f brady and white house budget 
director richard darman accepted a compromise proposal splitting 
the cost of the bailout so that only 40 percent of the 50 billion 
needed immediately would balloon the federal deficit 
the deal calls for the treasury to borrow 20 billion this year 
raising the estimated deficit from 149 billion to 169 billion 
and borrowing by a new agency to raise the 30 billion balance next 
year and the year after without counting that in the official 
deficit 
obviously weve only had an opportunity to make a quick 
review but based on that review in the spirit of which the 
president sent us here which was one of compromise we accept 
brady said 
the compromise was approved on a 2622 vote among house members 
of the conference committee despite vehement objections from rep 
dan rostenkowski chairman of the taxwriting house ways and means 
committee sen paul sarbanes dmd was the only one of the five 
senate negotiators to vote against the deal 
all of the money would be used to close some 500 insolvent sampls 
the bulk of them in texas and pay off savers whose federally 
insured deposits were lost through failed an often fraudulent loans 
the administration and congress had reached agreement long ago 
on the bulk of the legislation directing a massive overhaul of the 
industrys structure and regulation in an effort to prevent a 
recurrence of the cisis 
but a confrontation over the financing which one democrat 
characterized as a game of chicken had threatened to blow the 
