<TEXT>
the agriculture department says 1988 grain 
shipments from the united states remained of high quality even 
though drought cut yields 
the report by the federal grain inspection service released 
thursday compared inspection records from 1988 and previous years 
for wheat corn soybeans and other grains 
the report said wheat moisture decreased or remained the same 
for all lots except hard red spring wheat for hard red spring 
wheat the average moisture was 119 percent up from 118 percent 
in 1987 
wheat represented 36 percent of the total 1157 million metric 
tons of grains and oilseeds exported in 1988 
nearly half the 42 million metric tons of exported wheat was 
hard red winter wheat 19 percent white wheat 15 percent hard red 
spring wheat 14 percent soft winter wheat 2 percent durum and 
less than 1 percent mixed wheat 
the report said corn moisture and the amount of damaged kernels 
decreased but there was a small increase reported in broken corn 
and the presence of foreign material 
corn represented 407 percent of the total metric tons of grains 
and oilseeds exported in 1988 except for a fraction almost all 
was yellow corn 
soybeans showed an increase in test weight and a decrease in 
amount of damaged kernels but an increase in the amount of foreign 
material and split soybeans 
soybeans accounted for 157 percent of total exports of grains 
and oilseeds in 1988 the report said 
the other products are sorghum barley sunflower seeds rye 
flaxseed and oats 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the agriculture department has issued its 
first permit for the use of genetically altered trees under the 
notion that whats sauce for the potato is sauce for the poplar 
the department said the permit announced last week will enable 
investigators at iowa state university in ames to study a natural 
plant defense mechanism that has been transferred from the potato 
twenty poplar trees cloned for uniformity will be tested to 
see if the defense mechanism is switched on when the trees are 
threatened by insects and other pests thus saving plant energy 
when there is no threat 
the genetically altered trees wont be allowed to bloom or 
produce seeds usda says 
