<TEXT>
while many other stocks have reached or 
approached new highs of late shares of the big three us auto 
manufacturers have faced trouble getting into gear 
ford motor co for example traded late last week around 50 
down from the peak of 5675 it reached early this year 
chrysler corp in the neighborhood of 24 is going for barely 
half its 1987 high of 48 and general motors corp even with a 
recent spurt from the low 40s to 45 remains short of its 
early1989 high of 4737 
the groups laggard behavior is no puzzle to followers of the 
industrys fortunes car sales have been weak for some time now 
and production plans have been cut repeatedly for the remainder of 
the year 
indeed when wall street economists argue that the economy is 
headed for a recession the state of the auto industry is usually 
one of the first pieces of evidence they cite 
the weakness in the auto market has been quite obvious for 
months in disappointing car sales said kathleen heaney an 
analyst who follows the industry for nikko securities international 
in new york 
as a result the earnings of the big three will begin to 
reflect the strain 
some observers say the industry is paying a price for the 
marketing innovations that helped sell so many cars from the 
mid1980s through last year sales incentives such as rebates and 
cutrate financing and auto loans stretching out for periods as 
long as five years 
when consumers go shopping to replace cars bought with four or 
fiveyear loans they often find themselves with little equity in 
them to use toward a down payment on a new vehicle 
incentives are now the bane of every automaker selling cars in 
the us heaney says 
automakers have discovered that while they can no longer sell 
cars without some type of incentive this year they are learning 
that they cant even sell cars with incentives 
those problems aside many analysts argue that the industry was 
due for an inevitable down stage in its business cycle 
the longterm trend is for growth of the american car and truck 
fleet at about 13 percent a year the value line investment survey 
says in its latest quarterly report on the industry 
from 1984 through 1988 the advisory service says sales of 
vehicles surpassed that level using up a lot of demand we 
expect that unit sales comparisons will be negative through most of 
1989 wrote value lines mark leach 
all that doesnt mean however that everyone on wall street is 
down on the auto stocks viewed from a longterm perspective 
leach said industry fundamentals dont look all that bad 
the quality of domestically produced vehicles continues to 
rise and operating costs are being reduced all of which should 
ultimately lift earnings 
philip fricke an analyst at prudentialbache securities has 
just raised his ratings of the big three stocks 
we think the stocks are already discounting a severe sales and 
earnings decline next year which we dont think will happen he 
said 
the stocks tend to begin to outperform when the news 
background is bad when interest rates have peaked and are headed 
down and when a cyclical trough is in sight our call may be 
early but we think the greater risk is missing the move up 
says heaney although the outlook for the next year is not 
optimistic we would be looking for an opportunity to buy these 
stocks 
