<TEXT>
the younger brother of winemaking giants 
ernest and julio gallo has been denied a new trial in a trademark 
dispute that bars him from using the gallo name to sell cheese 
us district judge robert e coyle ruled friday that his 
association with a law firm that once represented the gallo winery 
is not a conflict of interest and that there is insufficient 
evidence to warrant a new trial 
the elder gallos sued the brother they raised after he began 
using the family name to sell cheese in the mid 1980s 
in his june 20 ruling coyle denied joseph gallo use of his full 
name as a trademark because consumers confused it with the famous e 
amp j gallo winery the ruling allows joseph gallo to use his name as 
a signature or in block letters if the label contains a prominent 
trademark without the gallo name 
a lawyer for joseph gallo joseph yanny argued in the retrial 
motion that his client didnt get a fair trial because coyles law 
firm represented gallo winery in a 1983 trademark dispute with 
gallo salame of san francisco 
coyle wrote in the decision that lawyers representing joseph 
gallo knew of his association with the law firm and hadnt 
objected when he was assigned the gallo cheese case 
coyle said he doesnt remember the earlier case which was 
settled before he became a district judge 
yanny also argued that the original ruling denied gallo his 
freedom of commercial speech as protected by the first 
amendment but coyle ruled that those arguments had been covered in 
the trial 
