<TEXT>
civilian unemployment dipped a tick to 52 
percent in july the government said friday analysts say the data 
should ease fears of an imminent recession but heighten concerns 
about inflation 
joblessness was down from 53 percent in june with nonfarm 
businesses adding 169000 jobs the labor department said 
at the same time junes job growth was revised from 180000 to 
250000 additional evidence that the economy continues to grow 
though at a slower pace than last year 
this suggests an economy that is clearly clearly far from a 
recession said elliot platt senior vice president of donaldson 
lufkin amp jenrette despite a lot of signs of economic weakness 
the labor market remains fairly strong 
michael boskin chairman of the presidents council of economic 
advisers said the report was good news and suggests the 
economy is continuing to expand 
while the job growth number provided encouraging news analysts 
were wary over data showing significant upward pressure on wages 
a welcome development for workers but a sign of stubborn inflation 
as well 
the labor department said average hourly earnings rose 08 
percent in july after increasing just 01 percent in the prior two 
months 
thats a very very powerful increase said platt 
ominous was the way boston co economic advisers inc chief 
economist allen sinai described the wage gains 
both agreed that julys wage increase should give pause to the 
federal reserve board which of late has relaxed monetary policy in 
hopes of fueling enough new growth to avert a recession 
there will be no more easing by the fed until after labor 
day said sinai 
the government said the unemployment rate fell last month even 
though civilian employment declined by 82000 people to 11745 
million the rate fell because of a larger decline of 146000 
people in the labor force the number of people who have jobs or 
are seeking employment 
the job growth again came predominantly in the service economy 
which accounted for 140000 of the 169000 new positions 
within services government employment was down by 25000 jobs 
but retail trade added 52000 wholesale trade 5000 
transportation and public utilities 23000 and finance insurance 
and real estate 11000 both business and health services posted 
modest gains the government said 
the goodsproducing sector added 29000 jobs with gains in 
construction and manufacturing offset somewhat by declines in 
mining and the automobile industry 
the 35000 boost in construction jobs came at the same time that 
housing starts and home sales were rebounding manufacturing posted 
a modest gain of 3000 positions after three consecutive monthly 
declines 
employment in the auto industry fell by 12000 jobs last monh 
after a decline of 16000 in june a slump coinciding with sluggish 
car sales 
employment in mining was down 11000 a figure heavily 
influenced by coal strikes in virginia west virginia and kentucky 
that have sparked wildcat actions in other coalproducing states 
the government said the average workweek for production and 
nonsupervisory employees in private industry increased by 03 
hours to 349 hours the factory work week held steady at 41 hours 
and overtime in july averaged 39 hours a week up from 38 hours 
in june the labor department said 
the jump in earnings brought average hourly pay in the private 
sector to 970 on a seasonally adjusted basis up from 962 in 
june 
the payroll and wage data are taken from the labor departments 
monthly survey of businesses a separate household survey found few 
major shifts in unemployment among demographic groups although 
joblessness among black teenagers fell to 274 percent last month 
from 365 percent in june the june total had been up from 324 
percent in may 
these were the july and june rates for other population groups 
adult white men 38 percent up from 37 
adult white women 43 percent up from 41 
white teenagers 134 percent up from 126 
adult black men 93 percent down from 94 
adult black women 99 percent down from 105 
hispanics 9 percent up fro 81 
a separate calculation of unemployment that includes members of 
the armed services stationed in the united states was unchanged at 
52 percent 
